  "description": "The Schwarzschild radius is the radius of the event horizon of a non-rotating, uncharged black hole:\nrs=2GMc2r_s = \\frac{2GM}{c^2}where MM is the mass, GG is Newton\u0026rsquo;s gravitational constant, and cc is the speed of light.\nKarl Schwarzschild derived this in 1916 as part of the first exact solution to Einstein\u0026rsquo;s field equations. The formula says the horizon radius is proportional to mass. For the Sun, rs≈3r_s \\approx 3 kilometers. For the Earth, rs≈9r_s \\approx 9 millimeters. For the supermassive black hole at the center of the Milky Way (~4 million solar masses), rs≈12r_s \\approx 12 million kilometers.\n",
  "name": "Schwarzschild Radius",
